The proposed system (see Fig. 2) for outlier prediction in this article consists of two core functionalities: (1) outlier detection in a stream and (2) outlier prediction in a stream. The outlier detection is an independent process, which is implemented using an autoencoder. The outlier detection continuously evaluates if the latest data point (xi\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbf {x}_i$$\end{document}) from a stream is an inlier or an outlier. The outlier prediction uses the results of the outlier detection to form the required training data. The outlier prediction is not an independent process, because it relies on the results of the outlier detection. Our study assumes that the data contains the required information for the outlier prediction without having an external source of data. The following subsections explain the proposed outlier detection and prediction in detail.

Outliers are detected using an autoencoder with a hidden layer of neurons, which use the sigmoid function as the nonlinear transformation. The proposed system defines an outlier as a data point (xi\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbf {x}_i$$\end{document}), which has an unexpectedly high value of the reconstruction cost (Eq. 11), given a distribution of values of the reconstruction cost. An outlier contains unexpected information, which cannot be modeled or reasoned with the available data. The unexpected information is observed as extreme values and deviations in the correlations of the data features. The feature values are scaled between 0 and 1 (xij∈[0,1]\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbf {x}_{ij} \in [0,1]$$\end{document}) as15xi=xi-xminxmax-xmin,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \mathbf {x}_i = \frac{\mathbf {x}_i-\mathbf {x}_{\min }}{\mathbf {x}_{\max }-\mathbf {x}_{\min }}, \end{aligned}$$\end{document}where xmax\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbf {x}_{\max }$$\end{document} and xmin\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbf {x}_{\min }$$\end{document} are vectors that contain the maximum and minimum values of the features, up to the evaluation of the current data point. The scaling is computed element-wise per feature. The limits of the features (xmax\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbf {x}_{\max }$$\end{document} and xmin\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbf {x}_{\min }$$\end{document}) are not known in advance, because a stream is unbounded. The limits are continuously updated when data arrives from the stream. However, the limits are not updated if the data point is classified as an outlier. This prevents outliers from affecting the outlier detection, because they are not allowed to modify the scaling limits (xmax,xmin\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbf {x}_{\max }, \mathbf {x}_{\min }$$\end{document}).

Let xi\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
