				\begin{document}$$P_\mathrm{c} = P_\mathrm{r}$$\end{document}) at the last possible iteration (Pc=1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$P_\mathrm{c} = 1$$\end{document}). This results in a total consumption of decmin-1∗d∗Pr\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathrm{decmin}^{-1}*d*P_\mathrm{r}$$\end{document} data points, because a maximum value of the reconstruction cost is d. If the model would reset the patience counter every time at the last iteration (Pc=1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$P_\mathrm{c} = 1$$\end{document}), and the reconstruction cost would decrease by decmin at a time, then M is the resulting number of consumed data points. The autoencoder uses a sigmoid activation function, which ensures that the reconstructed values per feature are between zero and one. As established, the input values are scaled between zero and one. Therefore, the maximum possible reconstruction cost is d.

Fortunately, M is a very conservative maximum bound of the required data points. Instead of constantly reducing the reconstruction cost by decmin, the autoencoder is expected to learn the hidden representation faster. Indeed, on average, the number of consumed data points for the calibration was 72 in the experiments in Chapter 5. In our work, we define M = 10,000 as the upper bound, which is suggested for the patience value in Bengio [8]. For the minimum decrease of the reconstruction cost (decmin), we utilize a value of decmin=0.01\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathrm{decmin}=0.01$$\end{document}, because it is a minor (1%\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$1\%$$\end{document}) improvement of the maximum reconstruction cost for data with one feature (d=1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$d=1$$\end{document}).

Our proposed method for outlier detection is calibrated and ready to use when (1) the scaling limits are calibrated (xmin<xmax\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
